{"title_page": "Nell Leyshon", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date = October 2015}}\n\n{{Use British English|date=October 2015}}'''Nell Leyshon''' is an award winning writer whose work alternates between prose, stage and radio drama. She was born and grew up in [[Somerset]], and spent half of her childhood in [[Glastonbury]], and the other half in a small farming village on the edge of the [[Somerset Levels|Somerset]] Levels. She had a mixed education, and ended up attending art college for a year before moving to [[London]]. A first career culminated in working as a Production Assistant then Producer in TV commercials for directors including [[Ridley Scott|Ridley]] and [[Tony Scott]]. She gave it up to spend a year in Spain with her boyfriend Dominic, who remains her partner. She returned pregnant. She attended the University of Southampton as a mature student. Only after the birth of her second son in 1995 she started to write seriously.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Spencer|first=Charles|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/theatre/drama/3662496/Playwright-who-ploughs-her-own-furrow.html|title=Playwright who ploughs her own furrow|date=2007-01-13|access-date=2020-04-20|language=en-GB|issn=0307-1235}}</ref>\n\nHaving taught adult students wanting to return to education when her children where young, she later decided to use her teaching skills to work with marginalised communities, including recovering addicts, mental health service users, gypsies and, in Labrador, aboriginal peoples. She taught and mentored creative writing and performance, focusing on developing skills and self-esteem, and, always, the writer's own original voice. In 2018 she founded The Outsiders Project a company giving voice to the unheard.\n\nShe spent 3 years on the Management Committee for the [[Society of Authors|Society of Authors,]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.societyofauthors.org/Groups/Scriptwriters/SWG-Committee/Nell-Leyshon|title=Scriptwriters Group {{!}} The Society of Authors|website=www.societyofauthors.org|access-date=2020-04-20}}</ref> and is on the Advisory Board of the [[Alpine Fellowship|Alpine Fellowship.]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://alpinefellowship.com/advisory-board|title=Advisory Board|website=The Alpine Fellowship|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-20}}</ref> In 2018 she became a trustee of [[Shakespeare's Globe|Shakespeare\u2019s Globe Theatre]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.shakespearesglobe.com/discover/about-us/|title=About us|website=Shakespeare's Globe|language=en-GB|access-date=2020-04-20}}</ref>, and is now Deputy Chair underneath [[Margaret Casely-Hayford|Margaret Caseley-Hayford]].\n\n=== Literary Work ===\n\n==== Prose ====\nIn May 2004, her first novel, ''Black Dirt'', was published by [[Picador (imprint)|Picador]] and was long-listed for the [[Orange Prize]] and runner up for the [[Commonwealth Writers|Commonwealth Prize]]. \n\nin May 2012, her third novel, ''The Colour of Milk'', was published by [[Penguin Books|Penguin]]. It was translated to multiple languages, winning the [[Prix Interalli\u00e9]] in France where it was also shortlisted for the [[Prix Femina]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.unitedagents.co.uk/news/colour-milk-shortlisted-prix-femina-etranger|title=THE COLOUR OF MILK shortlisted for the Prix Femina Etranger {{!}} United Agents|website=www.unitedagents.co.uk|access-date=2020-04-20}}</ref>, and voted the book of the year in Spain.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Camacho|first=Isabel Cristina Cuesta|url=https://elpais.com/cultura/2014/12/22/actualidad/1419263372_594947.html|title=\u2018Del color de la leche\u2019, mejor Novela seg\u00fan los libreros de Madrid|date=2014-12-28|work=El Pa\u00eds|access-date=2020-04-20|language=es|issn=1134-6582}}</ref> In 2015 her most recent novel, ''Memoirs of a Dipper'', was published.\n\n===== Radio Dramas =====\nHer first radio play, ''Milk'', won the [[Richard Imison Award|Richard Imison Award.]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130509160554/http://www.societyofauthors.org/radio-drama-previous-winners|title=Radio Drama Previous Winners {{!}} Society of Authors - Protecting the rights and furthering the interests of authors|date=2013-05-09|website=web.archive.org|access-date=2020-04-20}}</ref> Her second drama ''War Bride'' was runner up for the [[Meyer-Whitworth Award|Meyer Whitworth Award]].<ref>{{Cite news|last=Spencer|first=Charles|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/theatre/drama/3662496/Playwright-who-ploughs-her-own-furrow.html|title=Playwright who ploughs her own furrow|date=2007-01-13|access-date=2020-04-20|language=en-GB|issn=0307-1235}}</ref>\n\nSubsequent radio plays include ''Glass Eels'', ''Soldier Boy'', ''Writing The Century'' and ''Jess'', a [[Woman's Hour]] drama about child mental health for Children in Need. \n\n====== Theatre ======\nIn 2005 her play, ''Comfort me with Apples'', won an [[Evening Standard Theatre Awards|Evening Standard Theatre Award]]<ref>{{Citation|title=Evening Standard Theatre Awards|date=2020-04-01|url=https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Evening_Standard_Theatre_Awards&oldid=948525635|work=Wikipedia|language=en|access-date=2020-04-20}}</ref> for most promising playwright, was nominated for a [[Laurence Olivier Award]]<ref>{{Citation|title=Laurence Olivier Award|date=2020-04-17|url=https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Laurence_Olivier_Award&oldid=951477217|work=Wikipedia|language=en|access-date=2020-04-20}}</ref> and was shortlisted for [[Susan Smith Blackburn Prize|Susan Smith Blackburn Award]]\n\nShe adapted [[Daphne du Maurier|Daphne du Maurier's]] [[Don't look now (book)|''Don\u2019t Look Now'']] for the Lyceum, Sheffield which later transferred to the Lyric, Hammersmith. In 2010 her play ''Bedlam'' was the first written by a woman to be performed at [[Globe Theatre|Shakespeare's Globe]].<ref>{{Citation|title=Globe Theatre|date=2019-12-18|url=https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Globe_Theatre&oldid=931393492|work=Wikipedia|language=en|access-date=2020-04-20}}</ref>\n\nShe has also written plays for young people for [[National Theatre Connections]], ''The Beauty Manifesto'' and ''Terra''<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nationaltheatre.org.uk/file/connections-plays-2019-terraearth-nell-leyshon-0|title=Connections Plays 2019 {{!}} terra/earth by Nell Leyshon {{!}} National Theatre|website=www.nationaltheatre.org.uk|access-date=2020-04-20}}</ref> which was a dance theatre piece with choreography by Anthony Missem. She also wrote for [[Royal Theatre Plymouth]] and the play, ''The Word'', for [[RADA]] Elders group.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.rada.ac.uk/about-us/blogs/words-will-come-new-anthology-rada-elders-company/|title=The Words Will Come: a new anthology from the RADA Elders Company \u2014 RADA|last=Fabrique|website=www.rada.ac.uk|language=en-gb|access-date=2020-04-20}}</ref> \n\n====== Other Projects ======\nIn 2014 Leyshon wrote her first libretto, ''The River Keeper'', for Streetwise Opera,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.streetwiseopera.org/production/the-river-keeper/|title=The River Keeper|website=Streetwise Opera|language=en-GB|access-date=2020-04-20}}</ref> a charity which works with homeless people.\n\nIn 2018 she performed her one woman show, ''Three Letters'', at the Royal Shakespeare Company<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.rsc.org.uk/press/releases/rsc-mischief-festival-31-may-23-june-2018|title=Latest Press Releases {{!}} Royal Shakespeare Company|website=www.rsc.org.uk|access-date=2020-04-20}}</ref>, then at [[Edinburgh Festival Fringe|Edinburgh Fringe]] where it was broadcast on BBC Radio 3.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/m0000r3b|title=BBC Radio 3 - Drama on 3, Three Letters|website=BBC|language=en-GB|access-date=2020-04-20}}</ref> \n\n====== The Outsiders Project ======\nIn 2018 Leyshon founded The Outsiders Project, a company that gives voice to the unheard and marginalised through working with outsider artists and supporting their creativity. They work with members of the community of Boscombe, and the work is shown locally then shared with a wider world. The work is designed to develop authentic voices and is of exceptional quality. \n\nTheir vision is to show that people sidelined from society can write, perform and create work at the highest level. They support the outsider community to push boundaries to prove they can create work of outstanding quality and worth. \n\nThe Outsiders Project has produced three works for the stage; ''Vodka Hunte''rs, ''Secret Voices'' \u00a0and ''The Truth About Men'', all three as part of BEAF \u2013 Bournemouth Emerging Arts Fringe Festival 2018 and 2019.\n\nDuring the 2020 COVID-19 pandemic they launched the [https://www.outsidersproject-tattoo.com Tattoo Project]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.outsidersproject-tattoo.com/|title=Tattoos|website=Mysite 1|language=en|access-date=2020-04-20}}</ref> an online initiative to gather, tell stories and find new outsider artists.\n\n====== Teaching ======\nLeyshon has been teaching for 17 years specialising in outsider voices. She has worked extensively with the recovery community in prisons and mental health settings. She has also worked with the Gypsy community, and has led many partnership courses for [[Arvon Foundation|Arvon Foundation.]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.arvon.org/tutors/nell-leyshon/|title=Nell Leyshon|website=Arvon|access-date=2020-04-20}}</ref> \n\nOn YouTube, she created ''[https://www.youtube.com/channel/UCPckwLhvwG6wVhkCeohYTWg/featured The Lockdown Workshops]'', a series of writing classes designed specially for lockdown.<br />\n=== Selected Work ===\n\n==== Novels ====\n\n*''[[Black Dirt (novel)|Black Dirt]],'' ([[Picador (imprint)|Picador]], 2004)\n*''Devotion'' [[Picador (imprint)|(Picador]], 2008)\n*''[[The Colour of Milk (novel)|The Colour of Milk]]'', ([[Penguin Books|Penguin]], 2012)\n*''[[Memoirs of a Dipper]]'' ([[Penguin Books|Penguin]], 2015)\n\n==== Radio Dramas ====\n\n*''[[The Farm (play)|The Farm]]'' (2002) ([[BBC Radio 4]])\n*''Milk'' (2002) ([[BBC Radio 4]])\n*''[[Glass Eels (play)|Glass Eels]]'' (2003) ([[BBC Radio 4]])\n*''The Home Field'' (2003) [[BBC Radio 3|(BBC Radio 3)]]\n*''[[The House in the Trees]]'' (2004) ([[BBC Radio 4]])\n*''Soldier Boy'' (2005) ([[BBC Radio 4]])\n*''Black Dirt'' [[BBC Radio 3|(BBC Radio 3)]]\n*''[https://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/b00cc9hh War Bride]'' (2008) ([[BBC Radio 4]])\n*''[[Sons]]''  (2009)  ([[BBC Radio 4]])\n*''[[The Iron Curtain]]'' (2011) ([[Woman's Hour|BBC Radio 4, Woman's Hour]])\n*''[https://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/b01s4sz2 The Colour of Milk]'' (2013) ([[BBC Radio 4]])\n*''[https://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/b01ny48q Jess\u2019s Story],'' Children in need'', [[BBC Radio 4]]''\n*''[https://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/m0000r3b Three Letters] [[BBC Radio 3|(BBC Radio 3)]]''\n\n===== Theatre =====\n\n* ''[https://www.nellleyshon.com/plays/the-farm/ The Farm]''\n\n*''Milk''\n*''[https://www.nellleyshon.com/plays/comfort-me-with-apples/ Comfort me with Apples]'' [[Hampstead Theatre]]\n*''[https://www.nellleyshon.com/plays/dont-look-now/ Don\u2019t Look Now]'' (adapted from the story by [[Daphne du Maurier]]), [[Lyric Theatre (Hammersmith)]]\n\n* ''[https://www.nellleyshon.com/plays/the-beauty-manifesto/ The Beauty Manifesto]''\n* ''[https://www.nellleyshon.com/plays/the-river-keeper/ The River Keeper]'' [https://www.streetwiseopera.org/production/the-river-keeper/ Streetwise Opera]\n* ''[https://www.nellleyshon.com/plays/glass-eels/ Glass Eels]''\n* ''[https://www.nellleyshon.com/plays/bedlam/ Bedlam,]'' [[Shakespeare's Globe]]\n* ''Winter,'' [https://www.theatrenewfoundland.com Theatre Newfoundland and Labrador]\n* [https://www.rada.ac.uk/about-us/blogs/words-will-come-new-anthology-rada-elders-company/ ''The Word,'' RADA Elders group]\n* [https://www.britishcouncil.pe/en/programmes/arts/barro ''Barro'', Gran Teatro Nacional Peru]\n* [https://www.nationaltheatre.org.uk/file/connections-plays-2019-terraearth-nell-leyshon-0 ''Terra,'' National Theatre Connections]\n* ''Three Letters'', [[Royal Shakespeare Company]]\n\n=== Personal Life ===\nNell lives in Dorset with her partner Dominic. She has two sons.\n\n==== Agents ====\nBooks: [https://www.unitedagents.co.uk/cv/9300/books United Agents]\n\nTheatre: [https://www.unitedagents.co.uk/cv/9300/film_tv_theatre United Agents]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [https://www.nellleyshon.com Nell Leyshon Official Website]\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Leyshon, Nell}}\n[[Category:English dramatists and playwrights]]\n[[Category:Alumni of the University of Southampton]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date = October 2015}}\n\n{{Use British English|date=October 2015}}'''Nell Leyshon''' is an award winning writer whose work alternates between prose, stage and radio drama. She was born and grew up in [[Somerset]], and spent half of her childhood in [[Glastonbury]], and the other half in a small farming village on the edge of the [[Somerset Levels|Somerset]] Levels. She had a mixed education, and ended up attending art college for a year before moving to [[London]]. A first career culminated in working as a Production Assistant then Producer in TV commercials for directors including [[Ridley Scott|Ridley]] and [[Tony Scott]]. She gave it up to spend a year in Spain with her boyfriend Dominic, who remains her partner. She returned pregnant. She attended the University of Southampton as a mature student. Only after the birth of her second son in 1995 she started to write seriously.\n\n<ref>{{Cite news|last=Spencer|first=Charles|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/theatre/drama/3662496/Playwright-who-ploughs-her-own-furrow.html|title=Playwright who ploughs her own furrow|date=2007-01-13|access-date=2020-04-20|language=en-GB|issn=0307-1235}}</ref> \n\nHaving taught adult students wanting to return to education when her children where young, she later decided to use her teaching skills to work with marginalised communities, including recovering addicts, mental health service users, gypsies and, in Labrador, aboriginal peoples. She taught and mentored creative writing and performance, focusing on developing skills and self-esteem, and, always, the writer's own original voice. In 2018 she founded The Outsiders Project a company giving voice to the unheard.\n\nShe spent 3 years on the Management Committee for the [[Society of Authors]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.societyofauthors.org/Groups/Scriptwriters/SWG-Committee/Nell-Leyshon|title=Scriptwriters Group {{!}} The Society of Authors|website=www.societyofauthors.org|access-date=2020-04-20}}</ref>, and is on the Advisory Board of the [[Alpine Fellowship]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://alpinefellowship.com/advisory-board|title=Advisory Board|website=The Alpine Fellowship|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-20}}</ref>. In 2018 she became a trustee of [[Shakespeare's Globe|Shakespeare\u2019s Globe Theatre]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.shakespearesglobe.com/discover/about-us/|title=About us|website=Shakespeare's Globe|language=en-GB|access-date=2020-04-20}}</ref>, and is now Deputy Chair underneath [[Margaret Casely-Hayford|Margaret Caseley-Hayford]].\n\n=== Literary Work ===\n\n==== Prose ====\nIn May 2004, her first novel, ''Black Dirt'', was published by [[Picador (imprint)|Picador]] and was long-listed for the [[Orange Prize]] and runner up for the [[Commonwealth Writers|Commonwealth Prize]]. \n\nin May 2012, her third novel, ''The Colour of Milk'', was published by [[Penguin Books|Penguin]]. It was translated to multiple languages, winning the [[Prix Interalli\u00e9]] in France where it was also shortlisted for the [[Prix Femina]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.unitedagents.co.uk/news/colour-milk-shortlisted-prix-femina-etranger|title=THE COLOUR OF MILK shortlisted for the Prix Femina Etranger {{!}} United Agents|website=www.unitedagents.co.uk|access-date=2020-04-20}}</ref>, and voted the book of the year in Spain.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Camacho|first=Isabel Cristina Cuesta|url=https://elpais.com/cultura/2014/12/22/actualidad/1419263372_594947.html|title=\u2018Del color de la leche\u2019, mejor Novela seg\u00fan los libreros de Madrid|date=2014-12-28|work=El Pa\u00eds|access-date=2020-04-20|language=es|issn=1134-6582}}</ref> In 2015 her most recent novel, ''Memoirs of a Dipper'' was published.\n\nShe has been a speaker at multiple international festivals around the world including Hay Festival, Bogota Book Fair, Medellin, Mexico and Spain.\n\n===== Radio Dramas =====\nHer first radio play, ''Milk'', won the [[Richard Imison Award]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130509160554/http://www.societyofauthors.org/radio-drama-previous-winners|title=Radio Drama Previous Winners {{!}} Society of Authors - Protecting the rights and furthering the interests of authors|date=2013-05-09|website=web.archive.org|access-date=2020-04-20}}</ref>. Her second drama ''War Bride'' was runner up for the [[Meyer-Whitworth Award|Meyer Whitworth Award]].<ref>{{Cite news|last=Spencer|first=Charles|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/theatre/drama/3662496/Playwright-who-ploughs-her-own-furrow.html|title=Playwright who ploughs her own furrow|date=2007-01-13|access-date=2020-04-20|language=en-GB|issn=0307-1235}}</ref>\n\nSubsequent radio plays include ''Glass Eels'', ''Soldier Boy'', ''Writing The Century'' and ''Jess'', a [[Woman's Hour]] drama about child mental health for Children in Need. \n\n====== Theatre ======\nIn 2005 her play, ''Comfort me with Apples'', won an [[Evening Standard Theatre Awards|Evening Standard Theatre Award]]<ref>{{Citation|title=Evening Standard Theatre Awards|date=2020-04-01|url=https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Evening_Standard_Theatre_Awards&oldid=948525635|work=Wikipedia|language=en|access-date=2020-04-20}}</ref> for most promising playwright, was nominated for a [[Laurence Olivier Award]]<ref>{{Citation|title=Laurence Olivier Award|date=2020-04-17|url=https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Laurence_Olivier_Award&oldid=951477217|work=Wikipedia|language=en|access-date=2020-04-20}}</ref> and was shortlisted for [[Susan Smith Blackburn Prize|Susan Smith Blackburn Award]]\n\nShe adapted [[Daphne du Maurier|Daphne du Maurier's]] [[Don't look now (book)|''Don\u2019t Look Now'']] for the Lyceum, Sheffield which later transferred to the Lyric, Hammersmith. In 2010 her play ''Bedlam'' was the first written by a woman to be performed at [[Globe Theatre|Shakespeare's Globe]]<ref>{{Citation|title=Globe Theatre|date=2019-12-18|url=https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Globe_Theatre&oldid=931393492|work=Wikipedia|language=en|access-date=2020-04-20}}</ref>[[Globe Theatre|.]]\n\nShe has also written plays for young people for [[National Theatre Connections]], ''The Beauty Manifesto'' and ''Terra''<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nationaltheatre.org.uk/file/connections-plays-2019-terraearth-nell-leyshon-0|title=Connections Plays 2019 {{!}} terra/earth by Nell Leyshon {{!}} National Theatre|website=www.nationaltheatre.org.uk|access-date=2020-04-20}}</ref> which was a dance theatre piece with choreography by Anthony Missem. She also wrote for [[Royal Theatre Plymouth]] and the play, ''The Word'', for [[RADA]] Elders group<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.rada.ac.uk/about-us/blogs/words-will-come-new-anthology-rada-elders-company/|title=The Words Will Come: a new anthology from the RADA Elders Company \u2014 RADA|last=Fabrique|website=www.rada.ac.uk|language=en-gb|access-date=2020-04-20}}</ref>. \n\n====== Other Projects ======\nIn 2014 Leyshon wrote her first libretto, ''The River Keeper'', for Streetwise Opera,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.streetwiseopera.org/production/the-river-keeper/|title=The River Keeper|website=Streetwise Opera|language=en-GB|access-date=2020-04-20}}</ref> a charity which works with homeless people.\n\nIn 2018 she performed her one woman show, ''Three Letters'', at the Royal Shakespeare Company<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.rsc.org.uk/press/releases/rsc-mischief-festival-31-may-23-june-2018|title=Latest Press Releases {{!}} Royal Shakespeare Company|website=www.rsc.org.uk|access-date=2020-04-20}}</ref>, then at [[Edinburgh Festival Fringe|Edinburgh Fringe]] where it was broadcast on BBC Radio 3<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/m0000r3b|title=BBC Radio 3 - Drama on 3, Three Letters|website=BBC|language=en-GB|access-date=2020-04-20}}</ref>. \n\n====== The Outsiders Project ======\nIn 2018 Leyshon founded The Outsiders Project, a company that gives voice to the unheard and marginalised through working with outsider artists and supporting their creativity. They work with members of the community of Boscombe, and the work is shown locally then shared with a wider world. The work is designed to develop authentic voices and is of exceptional quality. \n\nTheir vision is to show that people side-lined from society can write, perform and create work at the highest level. They support the outsider community to push boundaries to prove they can create work of outstanding quality and worth. \n\nThe Outsiders Project has produced three works for the stage; ''Vodka Hunte''rs, ''Secret Voices'' \u00a0and ''The Truth About Men'', all three as part of BEAF \u2013 Bournemouth Emerging Arts Fringe Festival 2018 and 2019.\n\nDuring the 2020 COVID-19 pandemic they launched the [https://www.outsidersproject-tattoo.com Tattoo Project]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.outsidersproject-tattoo.com/|title=Tattoos|website=Mysite 1|language=en|access-date=2020-04-20}}</ref> an online initiative to gather, tell stories and find new outsider artists.\n\n====== Teaching ======\nLeyshon has been teaching for 17 years specialising in outsider voices. She has worked extensively with the recovery community, in prisons and mental health settings. She has also worked with the Gypsy community, and has lead many partnership courses for [[Arvon Foundation]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.arvon.org/tutors/nell-leyshon/|title=Nell Leyshon|website=Arvon|access-date=2020-04-20}}</ref>. \n\nOn YouTube, she created ''[https://www.youtube.com/channel/UCPckwLhvwG6wVhkCeohYTWg/featured The Lockdown Workshops]'', a series of writing classes designed specially for lockdown.\n<br />\n=== Selected Work ===\n\n==== Novels ====\n\n*''[[Black Dirt (novel)|Black Dirt]],'' ([[Picador (imprint)|Picador]], 2004)\n*''Devotion'' [[Picador (imprint)|(Picador]], 2008)\n*''[[The Colour of Milk (novel)|The Colour of Milk]]'', ([[Penguin Books|Penguin]], 2012)\n*''[[Memoirs of a Dipper]]'' ([[Penguin Books|Penguin]], 2015)\n\n==== Radio Dramas ====\n\n*''[[The Farm (play)|The Farm]]'' (2002) ([[BBC Radio 4]])\n*''Milk'' (2002) ([[BBC Radio 4]])\n*''[[Glass Eels (play)|Glass Eels]]'' (2003) ([[BBC Radio 4]])\n*''The Home Field'' (2003) [[BBC Radio 3|(BBC Radio 3)]]\n*''[[The House in the Trees]]'' (2004) ([[BBC Radio 4]])\n*''Soldier Boy'' (2005) ([[BBC Radio 4]])\n*''Black Dirt'' [[BBC Radio 3|(BBC Radio 3)]]\n*''[https://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/b00cc9hh War Bride]'' (2008) ([[BBC Radio 4]])\n*''[[Sons]]''  (2009)  ([[BBC Radio 4]])\n*''[[The Iron Curtain]]'' (2011) ([[Woman's Hour|BBC Radio 4, Woman's Hour]])\n*''[https://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/b01s4sz2 The Colour of Milk]'' (2013) ([[BBC Radio 4]])\n*''[https://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/b01ny48q Jess\u2019s Story],'' Children in need'', [[BBC Radio 4]]''\n*''[https://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/m0000r3b Three Letters] [[BBC Radio 3|(BBC Radio 3)]]''\n\n===== Theatre =====\n\n* ''[https://www.nellleyshon.com/plays/the-farm/ The Farm]''\n\n*''Milk''\n*''[https://www.nellleyshon.com/plays/comfort-me-with-apples/ Comfort me with Apples]'' [[Hampstead Theatre]]\n*''[https://www.nellleyshon.com/plays/dont-look-now/ Don\u2019t Look Now]'' (adapted from the story by [[Daphne du Maurier]]), [[Lyric Theatre (Hammersmith)]]\n\n* ''[https://www.nellleyshon.com/plays/the-beauty-manifesto/ The Beauty Manifesto]''\n* ''[https://www.nellleyshon.com/plays/the-river-keeper/ The River Keeper]'' [https://www.streetwiseopera.org/production/the-river-keeper/ Streetwise Opera]\n* ''[https://www.nellleyshon.com/plays/glass-eels/ Glass Eels]''\n* ''[https://www.nellleyshon.com/plays/bedlam/ Bedlam,]'' [[Shakespeare's Globe]]\n* ''Winter,'' [https://www.theatrenewfoundland.com Theatre Newfoundland and Labrador]\n* [https://www.rada.ac.uk/about-us/blogs/words-will-come-new-anthology-rada-elders-company/ ''The Word,'' RADA Elders group]\n* [https://www.britishcouncil.pe/en/programmes/arts/barro ''Barro'', Gran Teatro Nacional Peru]\n* [https://www.nationaltheatre.org.uk/file/connections-plays-2019-terraearth-nell-leyshon-0 ''Terra,'' National Theatre Connections]\n* ''Three Letters'', [[Royal Shakespeare Company]]\n\n=== Personal Life ===\nNell lives in Dorset with her partner Dominic. She has two sons.\n\n==== Agents ====\nBooks: [https://www.unitedagents.co.uk/cv/9300/books United Agents]\n\nTheatre: [https://www.unitedagents.co.uk/cv/9300/film_tv_theatre United Agents]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [https://www.nellleyshon.com Nell Leyshon Official Website]\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Leyshon, Nell}}\n[[Category:English dramatists and playwrights]]\n[[Category:Alumni of the University of Southampton]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n", "name_user": "Priedos", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Nell_Leyshon"}
{"title_page": "Bia (rapper)", "text_new": "{{Short description|American rapper}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = BIA\n| image              = https://www.refinery29.com/images/9649803.jpg\n| caption            = BIA in February 2017\n| birth_name         = Bianca Landrau\n| birth_date         = {{Birth date and age|mf=yes|1993|8|16}}\n| birth_place        = [[Medford, Massachusetts]], U.S.\n| occupation         = {{hlist|Rapper|singer|songwriter|model}}\n| years_active       = 2014\u2013present\n| module             = {{Infobox musical artist|embed=yes\n| genre              = {{hlist|[[Hip hop music|Hip hop]]|[[Contemporary R&B|R&B]]}}\n| background         = solo_singer\n| label              = {{hlist|[[I Am Other|i am OTHER]]|[[RCA Records|RCA]]|[[Independent music|Independent]]|[[Epic Records|Epic]]}}\n| associated_acts    = [[Ariana Grande]], [[Russ (rapper)|Russ]], [[Dove Cameron]]\n}}\n}}\n'''Bianca Landrau''' (born August 16, 1993<ref name =Goodrum>{{ cite web |author=Goodrum, Jasmine |date=24 April 2016 |title=Bia, the Perico Princess, came from the 'hood' to make her way to Hollywood |publisher=Niagara Frontier Publications |location=[[Grand Island, New York]] |url=http://www.wnypapers.com/news/article/current/2016/04/24/124460/bia-the-perico-princess-came-from-the-hood-to-make-her-way-to-hollywood |accessdate=2017-02-12}}</ref>), better known by her stage names '''BIA''' and '''Perico Princess''', is an American rapper, singer, songwriter and model who debuted on the [[Oxygen (TV channel)|Oxygen]] reality television show ''[[Sisterhood of Hip Hop]].'' She was signed to [[Pharrell Williams|Pharrell]]'s [[I Am Other|i am OTHER]] record label, in a partnership with [[RCA Records]], but has since signed a joint deal with [[Epic Records]].\n\n==Early life==\nOriginally from [[Medford, Massachusetts]], the rapper graduated Medford High School.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.boston.com/entertainment/music/2014/08/12/boston-rapper-bia-debuts-oxygen-sisterhood-hip-hop-aug/pVTR9PJbU5wK7tlbgvX9NO/story.html |title=Boston Rapper Bia Debuts on Oxygen's 'Sisterhood of Hip Hop' Aug. 12 - Music |publisher=Boston.com |date= |accessdate=2015-12-24}}</ref> She is of [[Puerto Ricans|Puerto Rican]] descent.<ref>{{cite web|last=Reichard |first=Raquel |url=http://www.cosmopolitan.com/entertainment/music/news/a37940/8-latina-rappers-who-are-killing-it/ |title=8 Latina Rappers Who Are Killin It in Hip Hop Right Now |publisher=Cosmopolitan.com |date=2015-03-19 |accessdate=2015-12-24}}</ref><ref name=\"youtube1\">{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=E-S4vyZnM-w |title=Bia Talks Impressing Pharrell, Having TI on Her Track + Drops Bars |publisher=YouTube |date=2015-09-02 |accessdate=2015-12-24}}</ref> According to an interview with [[Oxygen (TV channel)|Oxygen]]'s website, she spoke about wanting to become a rapper at a young age; after surviving a nearly fatal motorcycle accident, she decided to seriously pursue a career in rap/hip-hop.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.oxygen.com/people/bia |title=Bia &#124; Sisterhood of Hip Hop |publisher=Oxygen.com |date= |accessdate=2015-12-24}}</ref> The accident was in fact a result of drunk driver who crashed into Landrau and a group of friends in 2013.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.oxygen.com/sisterhood-of-hip-hop/season-1/blogs/bia-talks-about-working-with-pharrell-and-her-near-death |title=Bia Talks About Working with Pharrell, and Her Near-Death Experience &#124; Sisterhood of Hip Hop Blog |publisher=Oxygen.com |date=2014-07-24 |accessdate=2015-12-24}}</ref> The rapper stated \" When I was young in Boston, probably like 14, I used to hang with a bunch of rappers in the studio. They're famous battle rappers now. Back then, they were coming up. They used to be in the studio. I used to hit the 'record' button for them all the time. I was writing but I didn't tell anybody\"\n\n==Career==\nBia was initially discovered by her current manager, rapper [[Fam-Lay]] through [[YouTube]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://thesource.com/2014/08/13/her-source-womancrushwednesday-bia/ |title=Her Source &#124; #WomanCrushWednesday: Bia |publisher=The Source |date=2014-08-13 |accessdate=2015-12-24}}</ref> and later introduced to [[Pharrell]]. She was signed to the [[i Am Other]] music label as part of a collaboration with [[RCA Records]]. She has worked with the likes of rapper [[T.I]] as well as singers [[Jennifer Hudson]] and [[Usher (entertainer)|Usher]]. In late 2014, she released a mixtape entitled ''[[Chola Season|#CHOLASEASON]]''. She takes influences from American rapper [[Jay-Z]], Puerto Rican singer [[Ivy Queen]] and [[Selena]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.latinoshealth.com/articles/17516/20160128/5-latina-songs-need-listen-now.htm|title=5 Latina songs you need to listen to Now|work=Latino Health|publisher=Latino Health|author=Gonzalez, Stacey|accessdate=25 February 2016|date=28 January 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn an interview with radio station [[Hot 97]]'s morning show ''Ebro in the Morning'' in September 2015, she revealed that she will not be back for season 3 of ''Sisterhood of Hip Hop''.<ref name=\"youtube1\"/>\n\nBia was featured on [[J Balvin]]'s song \"[[Safari (J Balvin song)|Safari]]\", released as a single in May 2016.\n\nBia has performed at A3C, Art Basel, Revolt Music Festival, SXSW and [[Pusha T|Pusha-T]]'s ''Darkest Before the Dawn Tour''.\n\nAs the main support act on the North American leg of [[Ariana Grande]]'s [[Dangerous Woman Tour]], [[Little Mix]], were absent for some dates on, Bia took their place for those gigs.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://mobile.twitter.com/PericoPrincess/status/824824898791022592?ref_src=twsrc%5Egoogle%7Ctwcamp%5Eserp%7Ctwgr%5Etweet|title=Twitter|website=mobile.twitter.com}}</ref> Bia, alongside [[Victoria Mon\u00e9t]], was the main support acts of the European leg of the tour. \n\nIn 2017, Bia revealed that her new project was titled \"Trap Vogue\" and that it would not be her debut album but rather an EP to come before it. The EP would include all four previously released singles; \"Whip It\", \"Gucci Comin' Home\", \"Badside\" and \"Fungshway\" and would be released in the same year. In an interview with Hypebae, Bia described the project as \"high energy with Latin elements mixed in\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://hypebae.com/2017/1/bia-interview|title=BIA's Ready to Enlighten the Masses On her \"Trap Vogue\" Mentality|website=HYPEBAE|access-date=2020-04-15}}</ref> Bia also revealed that \"Esta Noche\" featuring Ariana Grande, which was performed during Bia's opening set for the Dangerous Woman Tour, would be included on the project. The entire project would eventually be scrapped in favour of new material.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://nylon.com/articles/bia-interview-perico-princess|title=Bia Talks About Her New Project, Touring With Ariana Grande, And Pharrell&#8217;s Best Advice|date=2018-09-21|website=NYLON|language=en|access-date=2020-04-15}}</ref>\n\nBia was featured on the track \"Miami\" from [[Kali Uchis]]' debut album [[Isolation (Kali Uchis album)|Isolation]], which was released on April 6, 2018.\n\nOn September 21st, 2018, Bia released the \"Nice Girls Finish Last: Cuidado\" EP which included the single \"Hollywood\" as well as collaborations with Kali Uchis and Kodak Black.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\nHer collaboration with rapper and singer [[Russ (rapper)|Russ]] on the single \"Best on Earth\" mentioned [[Pop music|pop]] icon [[Rihanna|Rihanna]] in the lyrics, which garnered her attention.<ref>{{cite web|title=itunes: Best on Earth by Russ & Bia|url=https://music.apple.com/us/album/best-on-earth/1483959502?i=1483959504}}</ref> The 13 time [[American Music Awards|American Music Awards]] winner posted a short video with the song playing in the background on her [[Instagram|Instagram]] page with the caption, \"Thank you Bia and Russ for my new fav song \"Best on Earth.\" The post gained over 19,000,000 views.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.instagram.com/p/B3x8FuDHOvQ/|title=Best on Earth|website=Instagram|accessdate=October 20, 2019}}</ref> The song eventually peaked at number 46 on the Billboard Hot 100 becoming Bia's highest peaking song on the chart and was certified Gold by the RIAA for selling over 500,000 copies in the United States.<ref name=\"US\" /><ref name=\"RIAA\" />\n\nOn March 27th, 2020, Bia released \"FREE BIA (FIRST DAY OUT)\" with the music video being uploaded on the same day. <ref name=\":0\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=6vqjUBso0_A|title=FREE BIA (FIRST DAY OUT)|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> A week later, on April 3rd, Bia released the lead single \"COVER GIRL\" from her upcoming project. The song was serviced to Urban and Rhythmic radios on April 14th.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200413130506/https://www.allaccess.com/urban/future-releases|title=Urban/UAC Future Releases {{!}} R&B, Hip Hop, Release Schedule and Street Dates {{!}} ...|date=2020-04-13|website=web.archive.org|access-date=2020-04-15}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200413125731/https://www.allaccess.com/top40-rhythmic/future-releases|title=Top 40 Rhythmic Future Releases {{!}} R&B Song and Hip-Hop Music Release Dates {{!}} ...|date=2020-04-13|website=web.archive.org|access-date=2020-04-15}}</ref>\n\n==Filmography==\n===Television===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Title\n! Role\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\" \n|| 2014\u20132015\n|| ''[[Sisterhood of Hip Hop]]''\n|| Herself\n|}\n\n==Discography==\n===Extended plays===\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|+ List of extended plays, with selected details, chart positions, and sales\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:9.5em;\" | Title\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:21.5em;\" | Extended play details\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | ''Nice Girls Finish Last: Cuidado''\n|\n* Released: September 21, 2018 <span style=\"font-size:85%;\">(US)</span><ref name=\":1\">{{cite web|title=itunes: Nice Girls Finish Last: Cuidado by Bia|url=https://itunes.apple.com/us/album/nice-girls-finish-last-cuidado-ep/1436098908}}</ref>\n* Label: RCA\n* Format: Digital download\n|}\n\n===Singles===\n====As lead artist====\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|+ List of singles as lead artist, with selected chart positions\n! scope=\"col\"| Title\n! scope=\"col\"| Year\n! scope=\"col\"| Album\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| \"Whip It\"<ref>{{cite web|title=itunes: Whip It by Bia|url=https://itunes.apple.com/us/album/whip-it-single/1110527759}}</ref>\n| rowspan=\"2\"| 2016\n| rowspan=\"4\" {{N/A|Non-album single}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| \"Gucci Comin' Home\"<ref>{{cite web|title=itunes: Gucci Comin' Home by Bia|url=https://itunes.apple.com/us/album/gucci-comin-home-single/1112738902}}</ref>\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| \"Badside\"<ref>{{cite web|title=itunes: Badside by Bia|url=https://itunes.apple.com/us/album/badside-single/1235855635}}</ref>\n| rowspan=\"2\"| 2017\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| \"Fungshway\"<ref>{{cite web|title=itunes: Fungshway by Bia|url=https://itunes.apple.com/us/album/fungshway-single/1238337415}}</ref>\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| \"Hollywood\"<ref>{{cite web|title=itunes: Hollywood by Bia|url=https://itunes.apple.com/us/album/hollywood-single/1435616941}}</ref>\n| 2018\n| ''Nice Girls Finish Last: Cuidado''\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| \"One Minute Warning\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://open.spotify.com/album/3joLqeZ63n9SpoeTuq0WLX?si=gcjrc1DrRkWRCKdqEZu17w|title=One Minute Warning by BIA on Spotify|work=[[Spotify]]|accessdate=August 19, 2019}}</ref>\n| 2019\n| rowspan=\"2\" {{N/A|Non-album single}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| \"FREE BIA (1ST DAY OUT)\"<ref name=\":0\">{{cite web|url=https://open.spotify.com/album/1GLlImH86rENUYXqMSTSUB?si=ypbNUaCCQky3H9_6bPv6uQ|title=FREE BIA (1ST DAY OUT) by BIA on Spotify|work=[[Spotify]]|accessdate=March 28, 2020}}</ref>\n| rowspan=\"2\" | 2020\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| \"COVER GIRL\"<ref>{{Citation|title=COVER GIRL|url=https://open.spotify.com/album/1K4CdZHyJW2VjSw8vZCQEr|language=en|access-date=2020-04-15}}</ref>\n|TBA\n|}\n\n====As featured artist====\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|+ List of singles as featured artist, with selected chart positions\n! scope=\"col\" rowspan=\"2\"| Title\n! scope=\"col\" rowspan=\"2\"| Year\n! scope=\"col\" colspan=\"9\"| Peak chart positions\n! scope=\"col\" rowspan=\"2\" style=\"width:11em;\" | [[List of music recording certifications|Certifications]]\n! scope=\"col\" rowspan=\"2\"| Album\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:2.5em;font-size:90%;\"| [[Billboard Hot 100|US]]<br><ref name=\"US\">{{cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/music/bia/chart-history/hot-100|title=BIA Chart History: Billboard Hot 100|work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|accessdate=December 18, 2019}}</ref>\n\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:2.5em;font-size:90%;\"| [[Hot Latin Songs|US<br/>Latin]]<br/><ref name=\"uslatin\">{{cite web|url= http://www.billboard.com/music/bia/chart-history/latin-songs/|title=BIA Chart history: Hot Latin Songs | work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]] | accessdate=October 29, 2019}}</ref>\n\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:3em;font-size:90%;\"| [[Hot R&B/Hip-Hop Songs|US R&B/HH]]<br><ref name=\"USR&BHHB\">{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/music/bia/chart-history/r-b-hip-hop-songs|title=BIA Chart History: R&B/Hip-Hop Songs Chart|work=Billboard|accessdate=October 29, 2019}}</ref>\n\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:2.5em;font-size:90%;\"| [[National-Report|COL]]<br/>\n<ref>*\"Safari\"{{cite web|url=http://national-report.com/nacionalColombia.php|title=TOP NACIONAL COLOMBIA Semana 43 del 2016|publisher=National-Report|accessdate=28 July 2016|archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6jLro2xPl|archivedate=28 July 2016|language=es}}</ref>\n\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:2.5em;font-size:90%;\"| [[Federazione Industria Musicale Italiana|ITA]]<br />