ctive=default-award&se=best+on+earth#search_section|title=Gold/Platinum: Bia - RIAA|publisher=[[Recording Industry Association of America]]|accessdate=January 30, 2020}}</ref>\n| ''Shake the Snow Globe''\n|}\n\n'''Notes'''\n{{notelist-ua}}\n\n====Guest appearances====\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|+ List of non-single guest appearances, with other performing artists, showing year released and album name\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:16em;\" | Title\n! scope=\"col\" | Year\n! scope=\"col\" | Other artist(s)\n! scope=\"col\" | Album\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| \"High\"\n| rowspan=\"2\"| 2015\n| [[Christian Rich]], [[Vince Staples]]\n| ''FW14''\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| \"Good Idea\"\n| [[Kid Ink]]\n|''Summer in the Winter''\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| \"Miami\"\n|rowspan=\"4\"| 2018\n| [[Kali Uchis]]\n|''Isolation''\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| \"Freak\" (Remix)\n| [[Victoria Mon\u00e9t]]\n|{{N/A|Non-album single}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| \"Seashell\"\n| Fasscoupe\n|''Hood Mascot''\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| \"Edible\"\n| Kayo Genesis\n|''Bad Sushi''\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| \"Perfect\"\n| 2019\n| [[Sam Spiegel]], Tropkillaz, [[MC Pikachu]]\n|{{N/A|Non-album single}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | \"Perfect (Remix)\"\n|rowspan=\"3\"| 2020\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | [[Cousin Stizz]], [[Doja Cat]]\n| ''{{N/A|Non-album single}}'\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | \"Labels\"\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | [[Kiana Led\u00e9]], [[Moneybagg Yo]]\n| ''Kiki''\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | \"Remember Me\"\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | [[Dove Cameron]]\n| {{TBA}}\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{IMDb name|6556991}}\n{{commons category inline|Bia (rapper)}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Bia}}\n[[Category:1991 births]]\n[[Category:21st-century American singers]]\n[[Category:21st-century American women singers]]\n[[Category:East Coast hip hop musicians]]\n[[Category:Hispanic and Latino American musicians]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Rappers from Boston]]\n[[Category:21st-century American rappers]]\n", "name_user": "Unrivaledla", "label": "safe", "comment": "Birthday was the wrong year and updated her photo", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bia_(rapper)"}
{"title_page": "Christon Gray", "text_new": "{{Infobox musical artist\n| name             = Christon Gray\n| background       = solo_singer\n| image            = Christon_Gray_Piano_Video_Shoot_in_New_York_September_2015.jpg\n| image_size       = \n| birth_name       = Christon Michael Gray\n| alias            = Flow Jackson\n| birth_date       = {{Birth date and age|1986|7|18|mf=y}}\n| birth_place      = [[Columbus, Ohio]], U.S.\n| origin           = Columbus, Ohio U.S.\n| death_date       = \n| genre            = [[Contemporary R&B]], [[Christian hip hop]]\n| occupation       = [[Singing|Singer]], [[songwriter]], [[rapper]], [[Record producer|producer]]\n| instrument       = [[Vocals]], [[Piano]]\n| years_active     = {{start date|2006}}\u2013present\n| associated_acts  = Kirk Franklin, [[Taelor Gray]], [[W.L.A.K.]], [[JGivens]], The Elevationists\n| website          = {{URL|christongray.com}}\n| Former Labels    = Fo Yo Soul/RCA, Collision Records\n}}\n\n'''Christon Michael Gray''' (born July 18, 1986) is an [[United States|American]] [[Rhythm and blues|R&B]] [[Singing|singer]] and [[Rapping|rapper]] born and raised in [[Columbus, Ohio]]. He is a [[Christians|Christian]] and calls his music \"about being human\". It is this approach that has allowed him to be successful as a mainstream artist.\n\n==Background==\nGray was born Christon Michael Gray on July 18, 1986, in [[Columbus, Ohio]]. His parents, Arthur Gray (a former choir leader), and his mother Leigh Ann (a trained [[soprano]]) have two other children; Christon's older brother, [[Taelor Gray]], who is also a rapper and [[pastor]], and his younger sister Aubrey, who is currently a college student. He resides in Cincinnati, Ohio with his wife, Shana Gray and has a daughter named Mya Blue. On February 22, 2020 they welcomed a baby girl, Story Monroe Gray.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.instagram.com/p/B-SeLt6jrEn/|title=Christon Gray on Instagram: \u201cStory Monroe Gray 02.22.20\u201d|website=Instagram|language=en|access-date=2020-04-20}}</ref>\n\n==Music career==\n\n=== 2006\u201311: Elevationists & EWEWM ===\n\nIn 2006, Gray was a part of The Elevationists with his brother, Taelor and childhood friend BJ (James Hazley). After a few years together, they disbanded the group.\n\nIn 2011, Gray, with the help of writing partner and music director Marlo Scott, released an album entitled ''[[Even With Evil With Me]].'' The independent release spawned the timeless track \u2018Isle of You\u2019, which quickly led to record label interest.  Before the year was out, he was signed to Collision Records.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.newreleasetoday.com/albumdetail.php?album_id=13892|title=School Of Roses by Christon Gray {{!}} CD Reviews And Information {{!}} NewReleaseToday|website=www.newreleasetoday.com|access-date=2016-09-14}}</ref>\n\n=== 2012\u201314: Collision Records & School of Roses ===\nIn 2012, he began working on his retail and label debut for Collision, but as it morphed, he decided to release it as a free mixtape.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.rapzilla.com/rz/music/freemp3s/5063-christon-gray-body-art|title=Christon Gray 'Body Art'|last=Horton|first=Chad|language=en-US|access-date=2016-09-14}}</ref> ''Body Art''  was a hit among Gray's fans and featured the label's roster as well as other artists and producers from the [[Christian hip hop|CHH]] genre. It caught many fans off guard because it was more of a rap album than EWEWM, which was the album's intention.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://wadeoradio.com/christon-gray-body-art-putting-the-art-back-in-artist/|title=Christon Gray \"Body Art\" \u2013 Putting the 'Art' back in Artist|date=2012-09-28|language=en-US|access-date=2016-09-14}}</ref>\n\nEarly in 2013, the label released the collective album [[W.L.A.K. (album)|''We Live As Kings (W.L.A.K.)'''''.''']] As a member of the four-man group, Christon was featured on the majority of the tracks. The album went on to top the [[Billboard charts|Billboard]] Gospel chart and crack the top 10 on the Rap and Christian charts. It also contained the cut '[[The Glory Album|King In Me]]' which was used as the theme song to [[American Idol]]\u2019s [[Super Bowl]] commercial in 2014.<ref>{{Citation|last=Christon Gray|title=American Idol Superbowl Ad (2014) ft. 'King In Me' by Swoope and Christon Gray|date=2015-03-30|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=oxbDZ8Irfo8|accessdate=2016-08-23}}</ref>\n\nOn March 25, 2014, Gray released his 2nd studio album entitled ''[[School of Roses]]''. It included fan favorites \u2018[[School of Roses|Vanish]]\u2019 (feat. [[Swoope]]) and \u2018[[School of Roses|Wanna]]\u2019 (feat. [[JGivens]]) which peaked at #15 on the [[Billboard charts|Billboard]] Live Trending chart. This was more of an R&B album than ''Body Art'', and it debuted at the top of the overall charts on [[iTunes]], and hit #44 on the [[Billboard Top 200]] and #5 on Top R&B Albums.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.christongray.com/promo/|title=PROMO|website=CHRISTON GRAY|access-date=2016-09-14}}</ref>\n\n=== 2015 \u2013 January 2017: FYS/RCA & The Glory Album ===\nIn early 2015, Gray began releasing music on his own, prompting fans to question whether or not he was still a part of Collision and [[W.L.A.K.]] The first track [[The Glory Album|'Open Door (See You Later)']] was posted on his [[SoundCloud|Soundcloud]] page in March of 2015.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://wadeoradio.com/new-music-christon-gray-open-door-see-you-later/|title=New Music: Christon Gray - \"Open Door (See You Later)\"|date=2015-03-20|language=en-US|access-date=2016-09-14}}</ref> Still not addressing his status, one week later he posted the beautiful piano led love ballad, [[The Glory Album|'Afraid With You']]. Lastly, he posted \u2018Light On\u2019 featuring [[B.Reith]] the following week. On April 28, 2015, after confirming he was leaving Collision in an interview with Wade-O<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://wadeoradio.com/christon-gray-talks-leaving-collision-the-demos-drops-new-freestyle/|title=Christon Gray Talks Leaving Collision & 'The Demos' + Drops New Freestyle|date=2015-04-09|language=en-US|access-date=2016-09-14}}</ref> & [[Rapzilla]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.rapzilla.com/rz/news/38-backstage/10579-christon-gray-pens-open-letter-about-collision-records-departure-announces-ep|title=Christon Gray announces departure from Collision Records, new EP|last=Daniels|first=David|language=en-US|access-date=2016-09-14}}</ref> Gray released an EP called ''The Demos'' to be streamed exclusively on the Christian music-streaming app, \"The Overflow<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://theoverflow.com/blog/christon-gray-to-release-exclusive-ep-on-theoverflow/|title=Christon Gray to release EXCLUSIVE EP on TheOverflow! - TheOverflow.com: Streaming Christian Music|date=2015-04-07|language=en-US|access-date=2016-09-14}}</ref>\".  The album went to be the most streamed project on the entire service for 2015, with all 5 tracks occupying spots #1 - #5 the week of its release.\n\nIt became clear that he was using these songs to get himself a new record deal, and in June 2015, he revealed that he had signed with [[Kirk Franklin|Kirk Franklin's]] label, Fo Yo Soul Recordings/[[RCA Records|RCA]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://christongray.com/|title=BLOG|website=CHRISTON GRAY|access-date=2016-08-23}}</ref> Kirk himself made the announcement via video screen at ''Alive Fest'' in Ohio on June 20, 2015.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.gospelpundit.com/2015/06/kirk-franklin-signs-singerrapper-christon-gray-to-fo-yo-soul-recordings/|title=Kirk Franklin Signs Singer/Rapper Christon Gray to Fo Yo Soul Recordings|date=2015-06-23|language=en-US|access-date=2016-09-14}}</ref> He subsequently removed ''The Demos'' to work on his third retail album and label debut.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://christongray.com/|title=BLOG|website=CHRISTON GRAY|access-date=2016-08-23}}</ref>\n\nOn November 18, 2015, [[Rapzilla|Rapzilla.com]] released an interview via email with Gray in which he said his debut with Fo Yo Soul had been completed and was being scheduled for release during \"the colder part of 2016\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.rapzilla.com/rz/features/interviews/12000-christon-gray-talks-upcoming-album-kirk-franklin-and-says-he-has-a-song-called-50-shades|title=Christon Gray talks upcoming album, Kirk Franklin and says he has a song called '50 Shades'|last=Daniels|first=David|language=en-US|access-date=2016-09-14}}</ref>\n\nA couple weeks later, on December 2, 2015, Gray released a freestyle video that included the name and release date of his next project, ''[[The Glory Album]]''. Gray's debut album with Fo Yo Soul/RCA was set to be released on March 11, 2016.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.rapzilla.com/rz/news/38-backstage/12079-christon-gray-reveals-release-date-of-new-album-alongside-freestyle|title=Christon Gray reveals release date of new album alongside freestyle|last=Daniels|first=David|language=en-US|access-date=2016-09-14}}</ref>\n\nTwo weeks after that, he debuted the first new track off the album on [[Vevo]] called \u2018[[The Glory Album|Connor McDees]]\u2019 featuring [[Brooklyn]] emcee, [[Skyzoo]] and his brother Taelor.\n\nLeading up to the album release, he was chosen as one of [[ESPN]]'''\u2019'''s Artists of the Month for March.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.espn.com/blog/music/post/_/id/8711/march-music-of-the-month-on-espn|title=March Music of the Month on ESPN!|access-date=2016-08-23}}</ref>  The station highlighted 3 tracks, \u2018[[The Glory Album|Open Door (See You Later)]]\u2019, '[[The Glory Album|The Glory Pt. I]]' and \u2018[[Stop Me (Christon Gray Song)|Stop Me]]' on all of their regular programing.  The later track went on to be used in commercials for [[Honda]],<ref>{{Citation|last=Honda|title=Another Milestone - 2016 Honda Civic Coupe :30|date=2016-05-06|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=tc_vRpmZT0E|accessdate=2016-09-14}}</ref> [[HBO]]\u2019s [[Ballers]],<ref>{{Citation|last=HBO|title=Ballers Season Two: Episode #2 Preview (HBO)|date=2016-07-17|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=4sRvnivFbbg|accessdate=2016-09-14}}</ref> [[Fox Broadcasting Company|FOX]]'s [[Lethal Weapon (TV series)|Lethal Weapon]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://twitter.com/search?q=Riggs%20&%20Murtaugh%20are%20always%20on%20their%20best%20behavior.%20Buckle%20up%20for%20the%20#LethalWeapon%20premiere%20Wednesday%20on%20@FOXTV!&src=typd|title=Riggs  - Twitter Search|website=twitter.com|language=en|access-date=2017-04-24}}</ref> & [[Roc Nation Sports|RocNation Sports]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.instagram.com/p/BIf3p8QAXZ9/|title=Instagram video by Roc Nation Sports \u2022 Jul 30, 2016 at 7:50pm UTC|website=Instagram|access-date=2016-09-14}}</ref> It was also used at the [[ESPY Award]]s during the shows final segment.<ref>{{Citation|last=Team USA Live|title=ESPYS 2016 - LeBron James Wins Best Male Athlete|date=2016-07-13|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=xowR2chp8NI|accessdate=2016-09-14}}</ref> The remix of the song was debuted during his interview on the [[Sway Calloway|Sway in the Morning]] show in mid September 2016.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://swaysuniverse.com/christon-gray-on-christian-groupies-marriage-challenges-racial-injustice-5-fingers-of-death/|title=Christon Gray on Christian-Groupies, Marriage Challenges, Racial Injustice + 5 Fingers of Death \u2013 Sways Universe|access-date=2017-04-24|language=en-US}}</ref> The song continued success in 2017, being used on [[FOX Sports]] programming worldwide, as well as the team song for a number of professional sports franchises. In 2018, the song was used as the theme to [[Warner Bros. Pictures|Warner Bros Pictures]] blockbuster '[[Rampage (2018 film)|Rampage]]'<ref>{{Citation|last=Warner Bros. Pictures|title=RAMPAGE - OFFICIAL TRAILER 2 [HD]|date=2018-02-13|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=-43MBOJnVks&t=17s|access-date=2018-10-06}}</ref> starring [[Dwayne Johnson|The Rock]] and as the intro song to [[EA Sports]] '[[Madden NFL 19|Madden '19]]' [[National Football League|NFL]] Video game.<ref>{{Citation|last=CurtWork|title=MADDEN NFL 19 ANTONIO BROWN INTRO [STOP ME] [CHRISTON GRAY]|date=2018-08-06|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Qr6MN7uUp_8|access-date=2018-10-06}}</ref> For the 2018-19 [[National Basketball Association|NBA]] Season, ESPN is using the song for its in NBA Studio show. In 2020, it was used by [[ABC Studios|ABC]] in some commercials for their show '[[For Life (TV series)|For Life]]'.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.instagram.com/p/B8CDS1ynnA-/|title=50 Cent on Instagram: \u201cyou gotta check me out in For Life on ABC. \ud83d\udd25#starzgettheapp #lecheminduroi #bransoncognac\u201d|website=Instagram|language=en|access-date=2020-04-20}}</ref>\n\nAlso during this time, [[Apple Music]] selected \u2018[[The Glory Album|Open Door (See You Later)]]\u2019 and \u2018[[The Glory Album|Ft. Knox]]\u2019 as \u2018Best of the Week\u2019 singles back to back. As well, TGA received key placements on [[Amazon Music]], [[iTunes]], [[Google Play]], [[Tidal (service)|TIDAL]], and [[Spotify]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.christongray.com/promo/|title=PROMO|website=CHRISTON GRAY|access-date=2016-09-14}}</ref>\n\n[[The Glory Album]] was released on March 11, 2016.  The LP went on to again claim the #5 position on the [[Billboard R&B charts]], while also hitting #6 on the Christian chart.\n\nGray was chosen as the first ever [[youth ambassador]]<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://rapzilla.com/rz/news/38-backstage/13666-christon-gray-was-first-ever-youth-ambassador-at-the-bet-awards|title=Christon Gray was First Ever Youth Ambassador at the BET Awards|last=Sarachik|first=Justin|work=Rapzilla.com|access-date=2017-04-24|language=en-US}}</ref> for the [[BET Awards]] in June 2016.\n\nAfter just one album with the label, Gray let fans know that he had officially left RCA in January 2017.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.christongray.com/|title=HOME|website=CHRISTON GRAY|language=en-US|access-date=2017-04-24}}</ref> He did not elaborate on the reasons, but said when the time was right he would speak about it. According to the post, it was a business decision and he wishes all parties involved well.\n\n=== 2017 - 'No Hesitation' and Return to FYS/RCA Records ===\nIn March 2017, Gray, along with Chris Shaban started their own Podcast entitled 'Chris' Podcast'. The first two episodes included guests [[Ty Montgomery]], [[Chris Broussard]] and [[Darren M. Haynes|Darren Haynes]]. Gray mentioned that this was a pilot program and that they were looking to bring it back sometime in 2019.\n\nOn July 28, Gray dropped a single called 'No Hesitation' independently. This was his first release since leaving Fo Yo Soul/RCA Records. In an interview with Wade-O, Gray said, \"You know the inspiration for the song came from me watching the BET Awards, and I saw 'Crae's speech, and I know he caught some flack for that... I talked to Lecrae the other day, and I told him, I come from that world... I grew up listening to them and without them, you (Wade) would not be having an interview with me... so I told him (Lecrae), yo, I didn't expect you to go back and apologize, so I did it for you.<ref>{{Citation|last=The Wade-O Radio Video Channel|title=Christon Gray on Story Behind \"No Hesitation\", Leaving RCA, and More|date=2017-08-07|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=wRy3B3VmH6E|access-date=2018-10-06}}</ref>\" The song would become another hit for Gray, and he went on to perform it live at the 2018 [[Stellar Awards]].\n\nA week later, on August 4, he released 'Shoulda Known', which included a sample of his song, '[[School of Roses|Burning House (Roses 102)]]' off the School of Roses album.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.instagram.com/p/BXi0W19hyaG/|title=Christon Gray on Instagram: \"My 2nd single 'Shoulda Known' featuring my brother @pray4jgivens is now available to stream worldwide. I've heard from a lot of School of\u2026\"|website=Instagram|language=en|access-date=2018-10-06}}</ref> It featured long-time collaborator and friend, [[JGivens]].\n\nOn Sunday November 5, Christon Gray was announced as the new Worship Leader at Christ's Church in [[Mason, Ohio]].<ref><iframe src=\"https://www.facebook.com/plugins/video.php?href=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.facebook.com%2Fccmasoncampus%2Fvideos%2F2111942965486135%2F&show_text=0&width=560\" width=\"560\" height=\"315\" style=\"border:none;overflow:hidden\" scrolling=\"no\" frameborder=\"0\" allowTransparency=\"true\" allowFullScreen=\"true\"></iframe></ref>\n\nBy the end of the year, an agreement had been reached for him to rejoin Fo Yo Soul and the new staff at [[RCA Inspiration]] in Nashville. It would not become public until later on in 2018.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://rapzilla.com/2018-10-christon-gray-rapzilla-chris-chicago-ep-115/|title=Christon Gray on Rapzilla.com LIVE with Chris Chicago - Ep. 115|website=rapzilla.com|language=en-US|access-date=2018-10-06}}</ref>\n\n=== 2018 \u2013 ''Clear The Heir''===\nBy the end of 2017 and leading into 2018, Gray let fans know that he was back writing, but did not elaborate.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.instagram.com/p/BcnRz4dh58O/|title=Christon Gray on Instagram: \u201cWRITING // 2018\u201d|website=Instagram|language=en|access-date=2018-10-06}}</ref> There weren't anymore indications until a post on Instagram in February with Chris Shaban and Ty Montgomery, taken from a writing session in [[Cambridge, Ontario]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.instagram.com/p/BfUDkEXBEhF/|title=Christon Gray on Instagram: \"All Amour\"|website=Instagram|language=en|access-date=2018-10-06}}</ref> He would later go on to tell that 4 songs were already written by this point, with two making the album, 'Seekrets' and 'Together Forever'.\n\nIn March, there came a string of posts from the studio that included MD and producer Marlo Scott, Producer GiAngelo Power, Pastor Trevor DeVage, Montgomery and Shaban. Gray said in a post on Twitter, \"...there was a week in March 2018 when everything started to come together. That week we did 'Grow Up', 'You & I (Sampson's Lament)' and brushed up a few other songs that made the cut.\"<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://twitter.com/christongray/status/1048606296893808646|title=Christon Gray on Twitter|work=Twitter|access-date=2018-10-06|language=en}}</ref> Those other songs were 'Seekrets', 'Together Forever' and the instrumental to 'Clear The Heir'.\n\nIn April at the Stellar Awards, rumors started swirling that Christon had re-signed with Fo Yo Soul/RCA Records, and while it had happened months before, it was a post with Kirk Franklin that said \"Welcome home\" that started the buzz.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.instagram.com/p/BhhiF08l83q/|title=Christon Gray on Instagram: \"Welcome home\"|website=Instagram|language=en|access-date=2018-10-06}}</ref> One more studio picture that month and Gray took some time off of his social media and no further updates came until late in the summer.\n\nOn August 2, a post from famed Canadian studio [[Metalworks Studios|Metalworks]] that read \"October 19\" and had no sound, but a studio full of his collaborators started his promotion run for the album.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.instagram.com/p/Bl_-DvdgWoM/|title=Christon Gray on Instagram: \"October 19\"|website=Instagram|language=en|access-date=2018-10-06}}</ref> It would come to light later on that October 19 would be the release date for the album.\n\nOn August 24, he dropped the first single 'Together Forever' with credit going to Fo Yo Soul/Essential Sound/Sony. The track contained a portion of his September 2016 interview on Sirius XM's 'Sway In The Morning' where he discussed divorce.\n\nOn September 14, he released the albums second single 'Time Out', produced by Toronto's GiAngelo Power. That instrumental had come from a writing session with JGivens in November 2016.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://twitter.com/christongray/status/1048612615449186304|title=Christon Gray on Twitter|work=Twitter|access-date=2018-10-06|language=en}}</ref> The song would go on to be featured on Spotify's 'Beastmode' [[Playlist]] and peak at #11 on Urban [[Christian contemporary hit radio|Christian CHR]] radio [[Nielsen Broadcast Data Systems|BDS]] reporting list, 'The Hot Chart'<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.instagram.com/p/BsGRzfGgwQN/|title=Christon Gray on Instagram: \u201cI serve the Lord and I\u2019m honored to represent Him wherever He puts me or my music.\u201d|website=Instagram|language=en|access-date=2019-04-12}}</ref>. It would spend 6 months on that chart.\n\nOn September 21, RCA released the music video for 'Time Out' and it featured a host of Christian athletes including Ty Montgomery, [[Mike Conley Jr.|Mike Conley]], [[A.J. Styles]], [[Steven Souza Jr.|Steven Sousa Jr]]., [[Andre Ward]], [[Michelle Plouffe]] and more. The songs co-writer and video director, Chris Shaban said, \"Growing up as a Christian kid (in Toronto), I was always inspired by athletes who excelled at a high level and love Jesus, so we decided we'd like to try and motivate the next generation the same way.\" It was accompanied by the #TimeOutChallenge that asked fans to rap over the songs instrumental with the winner receiving a signed pair of [[Air Jordan|Jordan Brand]] shoes from Conley and a signed [[Green Bay Packers]] jersey from Montgomery.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.instagram.com/p/BohDzU_B6S9/|title=Christon Gray on Instagram: \"Listen to my boy @mac11 aka \u2018Captain Clutch\u2019 and join the #TimeOutChallenge right now. His signed Jordan\u2019s and @ty_kingdomcitizen signed\u2026\"|website=Instagram|language=en|access-date=2018-10-06}}</ref>\n\nOn October 12, Gray released the third single from the album, 'Grow Up'. It was immediately added to numerous playlists on [[Spotify]], including 'New Music Friday', 'New Music Friday Christian', 'Blessings', and 'The Flow'. \n\n=== 2019 \u2013 Winner's Circle ===\nOne week after the release of Clear The Heir, Christon Gray was once again granted permission to leave RCA. While not speaking specifically about what led to his second request for release, it was granted and he wished the label success.\n\nA few months later he dropped the maxi-single, 'Winner's Circle', which featured the tracks 'Round Here' w/ [[Dee-1]] and 'All Day Flow'[https://www.instagram.com/p/B5BoRGeh7lW/]. He seems to have addressed his label situation on that song with the lines, \"Oh mamma mia, mamma mia, don't look so surprised when I see ya. When they pulled my album from the streamers (on release day), denied the label like I'm Peter. Fool me once, I can handle it. Fool me twice, turn my hand to fist, fool me thrice, I'll abandon ship.[https://genius.com/Christon-gray-round-here-lyrics]\"  He released the song to one radio station, BOOST 101.9 in St. Louis at their request, but kept it from other stations. The song peaked at #5 on BOOST, spinning more than 7 times a day at it's peak.\n\n==Discography==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n!Title \n!Details \n!US <br>R&B \n!US<br>Hip Hop/ R&B \n!US <br>Digital\n|-\n|''[[School of Roses]]''\n|Released: March 25, 2014\n\nLabel: Collision\n\n[[Compact disc|CD]], [[Digital download (music)|digital download]] \n;\n\n;\n|5\n|9\n|13\n|-\n|''[[The Glory Album]]''\n|Released: March 11, 2016\n\nLabel: [[RCA Records|RCA]]/ Fo Yo Soul\n\nCD, digital download\n;\n|5\n|14\n|22\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Official website|1=christongray.com}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Gray, Christon}}\n[[Category:1986 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:African-American rappers]]\n[[Category:African-American Christians]]\n[[Category:American evangelicals]]\n[[Category:American performers of Christian hip hop music]]\n[[Category:Rappers from Columbus, Ohio]]\n[[Category:21st-century American rappers]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox musical artist\n| name             = Christon Gray\n| background       = solo_singer\n| image            = Christon_Gray_Piano_Video_Shoot_in_New_York_September_2015.jpg\n| image_size       = \n| birth_name       = Christon Michael Gray\n| alias            = Flow Jackson\n| birth_date       = {{Birth date and age|1986|7|18|mf=y}}\n| birth_place      = [[Columbus, Ohio]], U.S.\n| origin           = Columbus, Ohio U.S.\n| death_date       = \n| genre            = [[Contemporary R&B]], [[Christian hip hop]]\n| occupation       = [[Singing|Singer]], [[songwriter]], [[rapper]], [[Record producer|producer]]\n| instrument       = [[Vocals]], [[Piano]]\n| years_active     = {{start date|2006}}\u2013present\n| associated_acts  = Kirk Franklin, [[Taelor Gray]], [[W.L.A.K.]], [[JGivens]], The Elevationists\n| website          = {{URL|christongray.com}}\n| Former Labels    = Fo Yo Soul/RCA, Collision Records\n}}\n\n'''Christon Michael Gray''' (born July 18, 1986) is an [[United States|American]] [[Rhythm and blues|R&B]] [[Singing|singer]] and [[Rapping|rapper]] born and raised in [[Columbus, Ohio]]. He is a [[Christians|Christian]] and calls his music \"about being human\". It is this approach that has allowed him to be successful as a mainstream artist.\n\n==Background==\nGray was born Christon Michael Gray on July 18, 1986, in [[Columbus, Ohio]]. His parents, Arthur Gray (a former choir leader), and his mother Leigh Ann (a trained [[soprano]]) have two other children; Christon's older brother, [[Taelor Gray]], who is also a rapper and [[pastor]], and his younger sister Aubrey, who is currently a college student. He resides in Cincinnati, Ohio with his wife, Shana Gray and has a daughter named Mya Blue. On February 22, 2020 they welcomed a baby girl, Story Monroe Gray.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.instagram.com/p/B-SeLt6jrEn/|title=Christon Gray on Instagram: \u201cStory Monroe Gray 02.22.20\u201d|website=Instagram|language=en|access-date=2020-04-20}}</ref>\n\n==Music career==\n\n=== 2006\u201311: Elevationists & EWEWM ===\n\nIn 2006, Gray was a part of The Elevationists with his brother, Taelor and childhood friend BJ (James Hazley). After a few years together, they disbanded the group.\n\nIn 2011, Gray, with the help of writing partner and music director Marlo Scott, released an album entitled ''[[Even With Evil With Me]].'' The independent release spawned the timeless track \u2018Isle of You\u2019, which quickly led to record label interest.  Before the year was out, he was signed to Collision Records.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.newreleasetoday.com/albumdetail.php?album_id=13892|title=School Of Roses by Christon Gray {{!}} CD Reviews And Information {{!}} NewReleaseToday|website=www.newreleasetoday.com|access-date=2016-09-14}}</ref>\n\n=== 2012\u201314: Collision Records & School of Roses ===\nIn 2012, he began working on his retail and label debut for Collision, but as it morphed, he decided to release it as a free mixtape.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.rapzilla.com/rz/music/freemp3s/5063-christon-gray-body-art|title=Christon Gray 'Body Art'|last=Horton|first=Chad|language=en-US|access-date=2016-09-14}}</ref> ''Body Art''  was a hit among Gray's fans and featured the label's roster as well as other artists and producers from the [[Christian hip hop|CHH]] genre. It caught many fans off guard because it was more of a rap album than EWEWM, which was the album's intention.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://wadeoradio.com/christon-gray-body-art-putting-the-art-back-in-artist/|title=Christon Gray \"Body Art\" \u2013 Putting the 'Art' back in Artist|date=2012-09-28|language=en-US|access-date=2016-09-14}}</ref>\n\nEarly in 2013, the label released the collective album [[W.L.A.K. (album)|''We Live As Kings (W.L.A.K.)'''''.''']] As a member of the four-man group, Christon was featured on the majority of the tracks. The album went on to top the [[Billboard charts|Billboard]] Gospel chart and crack the top 10 on the Rap and Christian charts. It also contained the cut '[[The Glory Album|King In Me]]' which was used as the theme song to [[American Idol]]\u2019s [[Super Bowl]] commercial in 2014.<ref>{{Citation|last=Christon Gray|title=American Idol Superbowl Ad (2014) ft. 'King In Me' by Swoope and Christon Gray|date=2015-03-30|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=oxbDZ8Irfo8|accessdate=2016-08-23}}</ref>\n\nOn March 25, 2014, Gray released his 2nd studio album entitled ''[[School of Roses]]''. It included fan favorites \u2018[[School of Roses|Vanish]]\u2019 (feat. [[Swoope]]) and \u2018[[School of Roses|Wanna]]\u2019 (feat. [[JGivens]]) which peaked at #15 on the [[Billboard charts|Billboard]] Live Trending chart. This was more of an R&B album than ''Body Art'', and it debuted at the top of the overall charts on [[iTunes]], and hit #44 on the [[Billboard Top 200]] and #5 on Top R&B Albums.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.christongray.com/promo/|title=PROMO|website=CHRISTON GRAY|access-date=2016-09-14}}</ref>\n\n=== 2015 \u2013 January 2017: FYS/RCA & The Glory Album ===\nIn early 2015, Gray began releasing music on his own, prompting fans to question whether or not he was still a part of Collision and [[W.L.A.K.]] The first track [[The Glory Album|'Open Door (See You Later)']] was posted on his [[SoundCloud|Soundcloud]] page in March of 2015.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://wadeoradio.com/new-music-christon-gray-open-door-see-you-later/|title=New Music: Christon Gray - \"Open Door (See You Later)\"|date=2015-03-20|language=en-US|access-date=2016-09-14}}</ref> Still not addressing his status, one week later he posted the beautiful piano led love ballad, [[The Glory Album|'Afraid With You']]. Lastly, he posted \u2018Light On\u2019 featuring [[B.Reith]] the following week. On April 28, 2015, after confirming he was leaving Collision in an interview with Wade-O<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://wadeoradio.com/christon-gray-talks-leaving-collision-the-demos-drops-new-freestyle/|title=Christon Gray Talks Leaving Collision & 'The Demos' + Drops New Freestyle|date=2015-04-09|language=en-US|access-date=2016-09-14}}</ref> & [[Rapzilla]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.rapzilla.com/rz/news/38-backstage/10579-christon-gray-pens-open-letter-about-collision-records-departure-announces-ep|title=Christon Gray announces departure from Collision Records, new EP|last=Daniels|first=David|language=en-US|access-date=2016-09-14}}</ref> Gray released an EP called ''The Demos'' to be streamed exclusively on the Christian music-streaming app, \"The Overflow<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://theoverflow.com/blog/christon-gray-to-release-exclusive-ep-on-theoverflow/|title=Christon Gray to release EXCLUSIVE EP on TheOverflow! - TheOverflow.com: Streaming Christian Music|date=2015-04-07|language=en-US|access-date=2016-09-14}}</ref>\".  The album went to be the most streamed project on the entire service for 2015, with all 5 tracks occupying spots #1 - #5 the week of its release.\n\nIt became clear that he was using these songs to get himself a new record deal, and in June 2015, he revealed that he had signed with [[Kirk Franklin|Kirk Franklin's]] label, Fo Yo Soul Recordings/[[RCA Records|RCA]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://christongray.com/|title=BLOG|website=CHRISTON GRAY|access-date=2016-08-23}}</ref> Kirk himself made the announcement via video screen at ''Alive Fest'' in Ohio on June 20, 2015.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.gospelpundit.com/2015/06/kirk-franklin-signs-singerrapper-christon-gray-to-fo-yo-soul-recordings/|title=Kirk Franklin Signs Singer/Rapper Christon Gray to Fo Yo Soul Recordings|date=2015-06-23|language=en-US|access-date=2016-09-14}}</ref> He subsequently removed ''The Demos'' to work on his third retail album and label debut.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://christongray.com/|title=BLOG|website=CHRISTON GRAY|access-date=2016-08-23}}</ref>\n\nOn November 18, 2015, [[Rapzilla|Rapzilla.com]] released an interview via email with Gray in which he said his debut with Fo Yo Soul had been completed and was being scheduled for release during \"the colder part of 2016\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.rapzilla.com/rz/features/interviews/12000-christon-gray-talks-upcoming-album-kirk-franklin-and-says-he-has-a-song-called-50-shades|title=Christon Gray talks upcoming album, Kirk Franklin and says he has a song called '50 Shades'|last=Daniels|first=David|language=en-US|access-date=2016-09-14}}</ref>\n\nA couple weeks later, on December 2, 2015, Gray released a freestyle video that included the name and release date of his next project, ''[[The Glory Album]]''. Gray's debut album with Fo Yo Soul/RCA was set to be released on March 11, 2016.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.rapzilla.com/rz/news/38-backstage/12079-christon-gray-reveals-release-date-of-new-album-alongside-freestyle|title=Christon Gray reveals release date of new album alongside freestyle|last=Daniels|first=David|language=en-US|access-date=2016-09-14}}</ref>\n\nTwo weeks after that, he debuted the first new track off the album on [[Vevo]] called \u2018[[The Glory Album|Connor McDees]]\u2019 featuring [[Brooklyn]] emcee, [[Skyzoo]] and his brother Taelor.\n\nLeading up to the album release, he was chosen as one of [[ESPN]]'''\u2019'''s Artists of the Month for March.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.espn.com/blog/music/post/_/id/8711/march-music-of-the-month-on-espn|title=March Music of the Month on ESPN!|access-date=2016-08-23}}</ref>  The station highlighted 3 tracks, \u2018[[The Glory Album|Open Door (See You Later)]]\u2019, '[[The Glory Album|The Glory Pt. I]]' and \u2018[[Stop Me (Christon Gray Song)|Stop Me]]' on all of their regular programing.  The later track went on to be used in commercials for [[Honda]],<ref>{{Citation|last=Honda|title=Another Milestone - 2016 Honda Civic Coupe :30|date=2016-05-06|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=tc_vRpmZT0E|accessdate=2016-09-14}}</ref> [[HBO]]\u2019s [[Ballers]],<ref>{{Citation|last=HBO|title=Ballers Season Two: Episode #2 Preview (HBO)|date=2016-07-17|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=4sRvnivFbbg|accessdate=2016-09-14}}</ref> [[Fox Broadcasting Company|FOX]]'s [[Lethal Weapon (TV series)|Lethal Weapon]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://twitter.com/search?q=Riggs%20&%20Murtaugh%20are%20always%20on%20their%20best%20behavior.%20Buckle%20up%20for%20the%20#LethalWeapon%20premiere%20Wednesday%20on%20@FOXTV!&src=typd|title=Riggs  - Twitter Search|website=twitter.com|language=en|access-date=2017-04-24}}</ref> & [[Roc Nation Sports|RocNation Sports]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.instagram.com/p/BIf3p8QAXZ9/|title=Instagram video by Roc Nation Sports \u2022 Jul 30, 2016 at 7:50pm UTC|website=Instagram|access-date=2016-09-14}}</ref> It was also used at the [[ESPY Award]]s during the shows final segment.<ref>{{Citation|last=Team USA Live|title=ESPYS 2016 - LeBron James Wins Best Male Athlete|date=2016-07-13|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=xowR2chp8NI|accessdate=2016-09-14}}</ref> The remix of the song was debuted during his interview on the [[Sway Calloway|Sway in the Morning]] show in mid September 2016.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://swaysuniverse.com/christon-gray-on-christian-groupies-marriage-challenges-racial-injustice-5-fingers-of-death/|title=Christon Gray on Christian-Groupies, Marriage Challenges, Racial Injustice + 5 Fingers of Death \u2013 Sways Universe|access-date=2017-04-24|language=en-US}}</ref> The song continued success in 2017, being used on [[FOX Sports]] programming worldwide, as well as the team song for a number of professional sports franchises. In 2018, the song was used as the theme to [[Warner Bros. Pictures|Warner Bros Pictures]] blockbuster '[[Rampage (2018 film)|Rampage]]'<ref>{{Citation|last=Warner Bros. Pictures|title=RAMPAGE - OFFICIAL TRAILER 2 [HD]|date=2018-02-13|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=-43MBOJnVks&t=17s|access-date=2018-10-06}}</ref> starring [[Dwayne Johnson|The Rock]] and as the intro song to [[EA Sports]] '[[Madden NFL 19|Madden '19]]' [[National Football League|NFL]] Video game.<ref>{{Citation|last=CurtWork|title=MADDEN NFL 19 ANTONIO BROWN INTRO [STOP ME] [CHRISTON GRAY]|date=2018-08-06|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Qr6MN7uUp_8|access-date=2018-10-06}}</ref> For the 2018-19 [[National Basketball Association|NBA]] Season, ESPN is using the song for its in NBA Studio show. In 2020, it was used by [[ABC Studios|ABC]] in some commercials for their show '[[For Life (TV series)|For Life]]'.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.instagram.com/p/B8CDS1ynnA-/|title=50 Cent on Instagram: \u201cyou gotta check me out in For Life on ABC. \ud83d\udd25#starzgettheapp #lecheminduroi #bransoncognac\u201d|website=Instagram|language=en|access-date=2020-04-20}}</ref>\n\nAlso during this time, [[Apple Music]] selected \u2018[[The Glory Album|Open Door (See You Later)]]\u2019 and \u2018[[The Glory Album|Ft. Knox]]\u2019 as \u2018Best of the Week\u2019 singles back to back. As well, TGA received key placements on [[Amazon Music]], [[iTunes]], [[Google Play]], [[Tidal (service)|TIDAL]], and [[Spotify]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.christongray.com/promo/|title=PROMO|website=CHRISTON GRAY|access-date=2016-09-14}}</ref>\n\n[[The Glory Album]] was released on March 11, 2016.  The LP went on to again claim the #5 position on the [[Billboard R&B charts]], while also hitting #6 on the Christian chart.\n\nGray was chosen as the first ever [[youth ambassador]]<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://rapzilla.com/rz/news/38-backstage/13666-christon-gray-was-first-ever-youth-ambassador-at-the-bet-awards|title=Christon Gray was First Ever Youth Ambassador at the BET Awards|last=Sarachik|first=Justin|work=Rapzilla.com|access-date=2017-04-24|language=en-US}}</ref> for the [[BET Awards]] in June 2016.\n\nAfter just one album with the label, Gray let fans know that he had officially left RCA in January 2017.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.christongray.com/|title=HOME|website=CHRISTON GRAY|language=en-US|access-date=2017-04-24}}</ref> He did not elaborate on the reasons, but said when the time was right he would speak about it. According to the post, it was a business decision and he wishes all parties involved well.\n\n=== 2017 - 'No Hesitation' and Return to FYS/RCA Records ===\nIn March 2017, Gray, along with Chris Shaban started their own Podcast entitled 'Chris' Podcast'. The first two episodes included guests [[Ty Montgomery]], [[Chris Broussard]] and [[Darren M. Haynes|Darren Haynes]]. Gray mentioned that this was a pilot program and that they were looking to bring it back sometime in 2019.\n\nOn July 28, Gray dropped a single called 'No Hesitation' independently. This was his first release since leaving Fo Yo Soul/RCA Records. In an interview with Wade-O, Gray said, \"You know the inspiration for the song came from me watching the BET Awards, and I saw 'Crae's speech, and I know he caught some flack for that... I talked to Lecrae the other day, and I told him, I come from that world... I grew up listening to them and without them, you (Wade) would not be having an interview with me... so I told him (Lecrae), yo, I didn't expect you to go back and apologize, so I did it for you.<ref>{{Citation|last=The Wade-O Radio Video Channel|title=Christon Gray on Story Behind \"No Hesitation\", Leaving RCA, and More|date=2017-08-07|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=wRy3B3VmH6E|access-date=2018-10-06}}</ref>\" The song would become another hit for Gray, and he went on to perform it live at the 2018 [[Stellar Awards]].\n\nA week later, on August 4, he released 'Shoulda Known', which included a sample of his song, '[[School of Roses|Burning House (Roses 102)]]' off the School of Roses album.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.instagram.com/p/BXi0W19hyaG/|title=Christon Gray on Instagram: \"My 2nd single 'Shoulda Known' featuring my brother @pray4jgivens is now available to stream worldwide. I've heard from a lot of School of\u2026\"|website=Instagram|language=en|access-date=2018-10-06}}</ref> It featured long-time collaborator and friend, [[JGivens]].\n\nOn Sunday November 5, Christon Gray was announced as the new Worship Leader at Christ's Church in [[Mason, Ohio]].<ref><iframe src=\"https://www.facebook.com/plugins/video.php?href=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.facebook.com%2Fccmasoncampus%2Fvideos%2F2111942965486135%2F&show_text=0&width=560\" width=\"560\" height=\"315\" style=\"border:none;overflow:hidden\" scrolling=\"no\" frameborder=\"0\" allowTransparency=\"true\" allowFullScreen=\"true\"></iframe></ref>\n\nBy the end of the year, an agreement had been reached for him to rejoin Fo Yo Soul and the new staff at [[RCA Inspiration]] in Nashville. It would not become public until later on in 2018.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://rapzilla.com/2018-10-christon-gray-rapzilla-chris-chicago-ep-115/|title=Christon Gray on Rapzilla.com LIVE with Chris Chicago - Ep. 115|website=rapzilla.com|language=en-US|access-date=2018-10-06}}</ref>\n\n=== 2018 \u2013 ''Clear The Heir''===\nBy the end of 2017 and leading into 2018, Gray let fans know that he was back writing, but did not elaborate.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.instagram.com/p/BcnRz4dh58O/|title=Christon Gray on Instagram: \u201cWRITING // 2018\u201d|website=Instagram|language=en|access-date=2018-10-06}}</ref> There weren't anymore indications until a post on Instagram in February with Chris Shaban and Ty Montgomery, taken from a writing session in [[Cambridge, Ontario]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.instagram.com/p/BfUDkEXBEhF/|title=Christon Gray on Instagram: \"All Amour\"|website=Instagram|language=en|access-date=2018-10-06}}</ref> He would later go on to tell that 4 songs were already written by this point, with two making the album, 'Seekrets' and 'Together Forever'.\n\nIn March, there came a string of posts from the studio that included MD and producer Marlo Scott, Producer GiAngelo Power, Pastor Trevor DeVage, Montgomery and Shaban. Gray said in a post on Twitter, \"...there was a week in March 2018 when everything started to come together. That week we did 'Grow Up', 'You & I (Sampson's Lament)' and brushed up a few other songs that made the cut.\"<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://twitter.com/christongray/status/1048606296893808646|title=Christon Gray on Twitter|work=Twitter|access-date=2018-10-06|language=en}}</ref> Those other songs were 'Seekrets', 'Together Forever' and the instrumental to 'Clear The Heir'.\n\nIn April at the Stellar Awards, rumors started swirling that Christon had re-signed with Fo Yo Soul/RCA Records, and while it had happened months before, it was a post with Kirk Franklin that said \"Welcome home\" that started the buzz.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.instagram.com/p/BhhiF08l83q/|title=Christon Gray on Instagram: \"Welcome home\"|website=Instagram|language=en|access-date=2018-10-06}}</ref> One more studio picture that month and Gray took some time off of his social media and no further updates came until late in the summer.\n\nOn August 2, a post from famed Canadian studio [[Metalworks Studios|Metalworks]] that read \"October 19\" and had no sound, but a studio full of his collaborators started his promotion run for the album.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.instagram.com/p/Bl_-DvdgWoM/|title=Christon Gray on Instagram: \"October 19\"|website=Instagram|language=en|access-date=2018-10-06}}</ref> It would come to light later on that October 19 would be the release date for the album.\n\nOn August 24, he dropped the first single 'Together Forever' with credit going to Fo Yo Soul/Essential Sound/Sony. The track contained a portion of his September 2016 interview on Sirius XM's 'Sway In The Morning' where he discussed divorce.\n\nOn September 14, he released the albums second single 'Time Out', produced by Toronto's GiAngelo Power. That instrumental had come from a writing session with JGivens in November 2016.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://twitter.com/christongray/status/1048612615449186304|title=Christon Gray on Twitter|work=Twitter|access-date=2018-10-06|language=en}}</ref> The song would go on to be featured on Spotify's 'Beastmode' [[Playlist]] and peak at #11 on Urban [[Christian contemporary hit radio|Christian CHR]] radio [[Nielsen Broadcast Data Systems|BDS]] reporting list, 'The Hot Chart'<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.instagram.com/p/BsGRzfGgwQN/|title=Christon Gray on Instagram: \u201cI serve the Lord and I\u2019m honored to represent Him wherever He puts me or my music.\u201d|website=Instagram|language=en|access-date=2019-04-12}}</ref>. It would spend 6 months on that chart.\n\nOn September 21, RCA released the music video for 'Time Out' and it featured a host of Christian athletes including Ty Montgomery, [[Mike Conley Jr.|Mike Conley]], [[A.J. Styles]], [[Steven Souza Jr.|Steven Sousa Jr]]., [[Andre Ward]], [[Michelle Plouffe]] and more. The songs co-writer and video director, Chris Shaban said, \"Growing up as a Christian kid (in Toronto), I was always inspired by athletes who excelled at a high level and love Jesus, so we decided we'd like to try and motivate the next generation the same way.\" It was accompanied by the #TimeOutChallenge that asked fans to rap over the songs instrumental with the winner receiving a signed pair of [[Air Jordan|Jordan Brand]] shoes from Conley and a signed [[Green Bay Packers]] jersey from Montgomery.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.instagram.com/p/BohDzU_B6S9/|title=Christon Gray on Instagram: \"Listen to my boy @mac11 aka \u2018Captain Clutch\u2019 and join the #TimeOutChallenge right now. His signed Jordan\u2019s and @ty_kingdomcitizen signed\u2026\"|website=Instagram|language=en|access-date=2018-10-06}}</ref>\n\nOn October 12, Gray released the third single from the album, 'Grow Up'. It was immediately added to numerous playlists on [[Spotify]], including 'New Music Friday', 'New Music Friday Christian', 'Blessings', and 'The Flow'. \n\n=== 2019 \u2013 Winner's Circle ===\nOne week after the release of Clear The Heir, Christon Gray was once again granted permission to leave RCA. While not speaking specifically about what led to his second request for release, it was granted and he wished the label success.\n\nA few months later he dropped the maxi-single, 'Winner's Circle', which featured the tracks 'Round Here' w/ Dee-1 and 'All Day Flow'[https://www.instagram.com/p/B5BoRGeh7lW/]. He seems to have addressed his label situation on that song with the lines, \"Oh mamma mia, mamma mia, don't look so surprised when I see ya. When they pulled my album from the streamers (on release day), denied the label like I'm Peter. Fool me once, I can handle it. Fool me twice, turn my hand to fist, fool me thrice, I'll abandon ship.[https://genius.com/Christon-gray-round-here-lyrics]\"  He released the song to one radio station, BOOST 101.9 in St. Louis at their request, but kept it from other stations. The song peaked at #5 on BOOST, spinning more than 7 times a day at it's peak.\n\n==Discography==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n!Title \n!Details \n!US <br>R&B \n!US<br>Hip Hop/ R&B \n!US <br>Digital\n|-\n|''[[School of Roses]]''\n|Released: March 25, 2014\n\nLabel: Collision\n\n[[Compact disc|CD]], [[Digital download (music)|digital download]] \n;\n\n;\n|5\n|9\n|13\n|-\n|''[[The Glory Album]]''\n|Released: March 11, 2016\n\nLabel: [[RCA Records|RCA]]/ Fo Yo Soul\n\nCD, digital download\n;\n|5\n|14\n|22\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Official website|1=christongray.com}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Gray, Christon}}\n[[Category:1986 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:African-American rappers]]\n[[Category:African-American Christians]]\n[[Category:American evangelicals]]\n[[Category:American performers of Christian hip hop music]]\n[[Category:Rappers from Columbus, Ohio]]\n[[Category:21st-century American rappers]]\n", "name_user": "MHMarch27", "label": "safe", "comment": "Linked 'Dee 1'", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Christon_Gray"}
{"title_page": "Kim Pawelek Brantly", "text_new": "<!-- Write the text of your article below this line. The first sentence should begin with the subject of your article surrounded by three apostrophes (for example: '''Article name''' is...) -->\n\n'''Kim Pawelek Brantly''' (born January 20, 1974) is a Vietnamese-American [[middle-distance runner|middle-]] and [[long-distance runner]]. She is the  woman's 1999 US [[USA Marathon Championships|Marathon Champion]].\n\n==Running Career==\n\n'''High School'''\n\nKim Pawelek Brantly began running long distance her senior year at [[Port Charlotte High School]].<ref>{{cite news |last1=Orazi |first1=Deborah |title=Coach, Student make Marks: Kim Pawelek and Bethany Morse Compete Against Each Other at Many Races |publisher=Sarasota Herald Tribune |date=January 11, 2000}}</ref> The very first time Pawelek ran, she came in last. Originally a [[sprint (running)|sprint]] runner, Pawelek began long distance running to train for soccer.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Rand |first1=Michael |title=Twin Cities Marathon Surprise! Marathon Novice Wins Women's Race |publisher=Star Tribune |date=October 4, 1999 |location=Minneapolis, MN |language=English}}</ref> \n\n'''College'''\n\nAs a senior at the [[University of North Florida]], Pawelek won [[NCAA Division II]] titles in the [[5K run]] and [[10K run]].<ref>{{cite news |last1=Coffey |first1=Wayne |title=She Comes A Long Way to Run a Marathon |publisher=New York Daily News |date=October 30, 2001}}</ref>\n\n'''After College'''\n\nPawelek went on after college to continue training for and running marathons, with many wins and finishes within the top 10 racers. Pawelek\u2019s most notable success was her 1999 [[Twin Cities Marathon]] win, which was the woman's [[1999]] [[USA Marathon Championships]]. The fast competition pushed her to her fastest marathon time of 2:37:56.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Rand |first1=Michael |title=Twin Cities Marathon Surprise! Marathon Novice Wins Women's Race |publisher=Star Tribune |date=October 4, 1999 |location=Minneapolis, MN |language=English}}</ref>\nAs Pawelek continued to train for marathons, she also had her sights set on trying for the [[Olympics]].  Pawelek participated in the 2000 Trials, and finished in 7th place,<ref>{{cite news |last1=Johnson |first1=David |title=Fast? Only if She Has to Be: Pawelek Plans to Pace Herself Sunday to Prepare for Olympics |publisher=Florida Times Union |date=December 12, 2003}}</ref> netting her $13,000 in prize money.<ref>{{cite web |title=2008 USA Women's Olympic Trials Marathon - Complete History 1984-2008 |url=http://www.marathonguide.com/news/exclusives/USAWomenOlympicTrials_2008/USAOlympicMarathonTrialsHistory.cfm |website=Marathon Guide |publisher=Web Marketing Associates (WMA) |accessdate=27 February 2020 |location=New York, New York |date=2008}}</ref>\n\n==Early and Personal Life==\nWhen Kim Pawelek Brantly was one year old, her family boarded a plane at the [[Saigon]] airport to escape the troubles of the [[Vietnam War]]. Shortly after their takeoff, further evacuation came to a halt due to the [[Bombing of Tan Son Nhut Air Base]].<ref>{{cite news |last1=Chavez |first1=Karen |title=Long-Distance Athlete Hopes to Take the Money and Run: Arden's Pawelek Supports Self Through Her Sport - And Looks to Win Big in the Future |publisher=Asheville Citizen - Times |date=October 8, 2004}}</ref> After arriving in the United States, Pawelek\u2019s family began life in the United States in Baltimore, then moved to Thorp, Wisconsin where Pawelek\u2019s mother attended elementary school with her daughters. Later, the family moved again to Port Charlotte, Florida when Pawelek was a preteen.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Longman |first1=Jere |title=Without Mom's Blessing, a Marathoner Drives On |publisher=New York Times |date=February 26, 2000}}</ref> When she was 14, Pawelek\u2019s father Alan and mother Linda Nguyen separated. Eventually, Nguyen wanted to move Pawelek and her sister Mary to Texas, but Pawelek refused. Despite initial disagreement, Nguyen decided to allow Pawelek to remain in Florida. Pawelek attended high school and college in Florida, where her running career began.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Chavez |first1=Karen |title=Long-Distance Athlete Hopes to Take the Money and Run: Arden's Pawelek Supports Self Through Her Sport - And Looks to Win Big in the Future |publisher=Asheville Citizen - Times |date=October 8, 2004}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Longman |first1=Jere |title=Olympics; Without Mom's Blessing, A Marathoner Drives On |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2000/02/26/sports/olympics-without-mom-s-blessing-a-marathoner-drives-on.html |website=New York Times |publisher=New York Times Company |accessdate=October 7, 2019}}</ref>.\n\nPawelek is married to [[Keith Brantly]], a former professional [[long-distance runner]].<ref>{{cite news |last1=Chavez |first1=Karen |title=Long-Distance Athlete Hopes to Take the Money and Run: Arden's Pawelek Supports Self Through Her Sport - And Looks to Win Big in the Future |publisher=Asheville Citizen - Times |date=October 8, 2004}}</ref>\n\n==Achievements==\n\n{| {{AchievementTable|Event=yes}}\n\n|-\n|1999\n|[[Athletics at the 1999 Summer Universiade \u2013 Women's half marathon|Summer Universiade Half Marathon]]\n|[[Palma de Mallorca, Spain]] \n|5th\n|Half marathon\n|1:15:47<ref>[http://sportfieber.pytalhost.com/l/leichtathletik/1999/1999.World%20University%20Games.By%20Day.pdf Results] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140503223712/http://sportfieber.pytalhost.com/l/leichtathletik/1999/1999.World%20University%20Games.By%20Day.pdf |date=2014-05-03 }}</ref>\n|-\n|1999\n|[[Twin Cities Marathon]]\n|[[Minneapolis\u2013Saint Paul]] \n|bgcolor=\"gold\" | 1st\n|Marathon\n|2:37:56<ref name=\"Andy Milroy\">{{cite web |title=ARRS - Runner: Kim Brantly Pawelek |url=https://more.arrs.run/runner/2150 |website=Association of Road Racing Statisticians}}</ref>\n|-\n|2000\n|[[United States Olympic Trials (track and field)|US Olympic Marathon Trials]]\n|[[Columbia, South Carolina]]\n|7th\n|Marathon\n|2:39:16<ref>{{cite web |title=2008 USA Women's Olympic Trials Marathon - Complete History 1984-2008 |url=http://www.marathonguide.com/news/exclusives/USAWomenOlympicTrials_2008/USAOlympicMarathonTrialsHistory.cfm |website=Marathon Guide |publisher=Web Marketing Associates (WMA) |accessdate=27 February 2020 |location=New York, New York |date=2008}}</ref>\n|-\n|2000\n|[[Walt Disney World Marathon|Walt Disney World Half Marathon]]\n|[[Orlando, Florida]] \n|bgcolor=\"gold\" | 1st\n|Half-marathon\n|1:15:19<ref>{{cite web |title=Marathon and Half Marathon All-Time Records |url=https://disneysportsnews.com/walt-disney-world-marathon-and-half-marathon-all-time-records/ |website=Disney Sports News |publisher=Disney |accessdate=26 February 2020 |location=Lake Buena Vista, Florida |date=1 January 2013}}</ref>\n|-\n|2001\n|[[Walt Disney World Marathon|Walt Disney World Half Marathon]]\n|[[Orlando, Florida]] \n|bgcolor=\"gold\" | 1st\n|Half marathon\n|1:16:46<ref>{{cite web |title=Marathon and Half Marathon All-Time Records |url=https://disneysportsnews.com/walt-disney-world-marathon-and-half-marathon-all-time-records/ |website=Disney Sports News |publisher=Disney |accessdate=26 February 2020 |location=Lake Buena Vista, Florida |date=1 January 2013}}</ref>\n|-\n|2002\n|[[2002 IAAF World Half Marathon Championships|IAAF World Half Marathon Championship]]\n|[[Brussels, Belgium]] \n|54th\n|Half marathon\n|1:17:30<ref name=iaaf_01>\n{{ Citation \n| last = \n| first =  \n| date = \n| title = IAAF WORLD HALF MARATHON CHAMPIONSHIPS - KAVARNA 2012 - FACTS & FIGURES - Incorporating the IAAF World Half Marathon Championships (1992-2005/2008-2010) & the IAAF World Road Running Championships 2006/2007\n| url = http://dt9guucc6nuua.cloudfront.net/competitioninfo/4338c03a-914e-4df3-ac47-68e78067142c.pdf\n| publisher = [[IAAF]]\n| page = \n| language = \n| accessdate = September 1, 2013\n}}\n</ref>\n|-\n|2004\n|[